<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>
        <%= title %> | Forecasting Recessions
    </title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
</head>

<body>
    <%- include('partials/header') %>

        <main>
            <h1>Analysis Methods</h1>
            <section>
                <h2>1. Methodology</h2>
                <h3>1.1 Overview</h3>
                <p>The analysis systematically measures how closely current U.S. economic indicator trends resemble the
                    pre-recession periods of eight historical U.S. recessions. Rather than relying on visual inspection
                    alone, two quantitative metrics are computed for every combination of recession, indicator, and time
                    window — producing a composite similarity score from 0 to 100.</p>

                <br>
                <h3>1.2. Indicators</h3>
                <p>Six key economic indicators were selected to capture different facets of the economy:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Unemployment</strong> — the unemployment rate (seasonally adjusted)</li>
                    <li><strong>Interest rates</strong> — the federal funds rate (monthly average)</li>
                    <li><strong>Oil prices</strong> — the price of West Texas Intermediate crude oil (monthly average)
                    </li>
                    <li><strong>SP500</strong> — the S&P 500 index (monthly close)</li>
                    <li><strong>VIX</strong> — the CBOE Volatility Index (daily close, monthly average)</li>
                    <li><strong>Gold</strong> — the price of gold (monthly close)</li>
                </ul>
                <br>
                <h3>1.3 Time Windows Compared</h3>
                <p>For each recession, indicator data was extracted for six look-back windows ending at the month before
                    the recession officially began. The same windows were applied to current data ending March 2026.
                    This allows a like-for-like comparison of how each indicator behaved at equivalent points in time
                    before each historical recession versus today.</p>

                <table class="table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Window</th>
                            <th>Interpretation</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1 Month</strong></td>
                            <td>Very near-term momentum — the most recent trend direction</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2 Months</strong></td>
                            <td>Short-term trend — captures early shifts in indicator direction</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>3 Months</strong></td>
                            <td>Quarter-level trend — most useful for fast-moving indicators (VIX, Oil, SP500)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>6 Months</strong></td>
                            <td>Medium-term trend — captures policy-response lags (e.g. Fed rate decisions)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1 Year</strong></td>
                            <td>One-year arc — most useful for slow-moving indicators (Unemployment, Interest)</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2 Years</strong></td>
                            <td>Full cycle view — captures the macro environment leading into a recession</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>

                <br>
                <h3>1.4 Metric 1 — Pearson Correlation</h3>
                <p>Pearson correlation measures the degree to which two time series move in the same direction over the
                    same period. It ranges from -1 to +1, where:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>+1.0</strong> means the two series move in perfect lockstep — when one rises, the other
                        rises by a proportional amount.</li>
                    <li><strong>0.0</strong> means there is no linear relationship between the two series — movements
                        are unrelated.</li>
                    <li><strong>-1.0</strong> means the series move in exactly opposite directions.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>In the context of this analysis, a Pearson score close to +1 indicates that the current indicator
                    trend is moving in the same direction and with the same relative intensity as the pre-recession
                    trend for a given historical recession. This is particularly informative for indicators with clear
                    directional signals — for example, whether unemployment is rising or falling — but it does not
                    account for timing differences or shape nuances within the window.</p>
                <p>The raw Pearson value is rescaled from [-1, +1] to [0, 100] to make it compatible with the composite
                    score, using the formula: <code>Pearson Score = (r + 1) / 2 × 100</code>.</p>

                <br>
                <h3>1.5 Metric 2 — Dynamic Time Warping (DTW)</h3>
                <p>Dynamic Time Warping (DTW) is a shape-matching algorithm that measures how similar two time series
                    are in terms of their overall pattern, even when they are slightly offset in time. Unlike Pearson
                    correlation, DTW can detect that two series have the same general trajectory even if one is leading
                    or lagging the other by a few months — a common feature of economic indicator data.</p>
                <p>Before computing DTW, each indicator series is min-max normalised to the range [0, 1]. This
                    eliminates scale differences between indicators (e.g. Oil prices in the hundreds vs Unemployment in
                    single digits) so that the shape comparison is fair and scale-invariant.</p>
                <p>DTW returns a distance value — lower distances mean the shapes are more similar. This is converted to
                    a similarity score [0, 100] by dividing the raw distance by the theoretical maximum distance for
                    sequences of that length, then inverting the result:
                    <code>DTW Score = (1 - distance / max_distance) × 100</code>.
                </p>

                <br>
                <h3>1.6 Composite Score</h3>
                <p>The composite score is an equal-weighted average of the Pearson and DTW scores:
                    <code>Composite = 0.5 × Pearson Score + 0.5 × DTW Score</code>. A composite score of 60 or above is
                    flagged as a 'notable match' in this analysis. This threshold was chosen based on the distribution
                    of scores across all comparisons — the majority of scores fall below 60, making higher values
                    meaningful.
                </p>

                <br>
                <h3>1.7 Recessions Analysed</h3>
                <p>Eight U.S. recessions were included, covering a range of economic triggers:</p>

                <table class="table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Recession</th>
                            <th>Primary Cause</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1969 Vietnam/Fed Tightening</strong></td>
                            <td>Post-war spending + aggressive Fed rate hikes to control inflation</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1973 Oil Embargo Stagflation</strong></td>
                            <td>OPEC oil embargo caused energy crisis and stagflation</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1980 Volcker Inflation Fight</strong></td>
                            <td>Paul Volcker's Fed sharply raised rates to break the inflation cycle</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1981 High Interest Rates</strong></td>
                            <td>Continuation of Volcker policy; deepest post-WWII unemployment at the time</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>1990 Gulf War Oil Shock</strong></td>
                            <td>Gulf War oil shock combined with the savings and loan crisis</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2001 Dot-Com Bust</strong></td>
                            <td>Collapse of overvalued tech sector, stock market crash, 9/11</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2008 Great Recession</strong></td>
                            <td>Housing bubble collapse, banking system failure, credit freeze</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>2020 COVID Pandemic</strong></td>
                            <td>Sudden global pandemic-driven economic shutdown</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </section>
        </main>

        <%- include('partials/footer') %>
</body>

</html>